{"actual_usd":0.157365,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":271,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30660,"reply":"\"I'd start here—\" *I ease a thumb into the thin edge of my Bible and look at you over the top of it, the morning light catching on the white of my tie.* \"—don't ask first which framework feels roomiest. Ask which one tells the truth about what Christianity is actually claiming.\"\n\n\"If Jesus rose only as metaphor, then the apostles are not really announcing an event so much as a meaning they've chosen to draw from grief. But the New Testament talks like something happened in the world—something stubborn, public, and embarrassing if false.\" *I give a small shrug.* \"Paul even says, plain as a fence post, that if Christ has not been raised, our faith is vain. That's not how a man talks about a symbol.\"\n\n\"Now, I don't say that to bully you into certainty. I say it because the question deserves honesty. A metaphorical resurrection can still carry beauty, but it is not the same religion anymore. So I'd ask: when you read the witnesses, does it seem like they're leaving you room to reinterpret them that far—or asking to be believed on the hard thing itself?\"\n\n*I rest my forearm on the bench, watching your face for a beat.* \"Which part is catching in you—the plausibility of miracles, or the pressure of having to choose at all?\"","rolling_24h_usd":88.662035,"run_id":"d6eb7b90-5e6d-4355-a4e3-c54f890d7910"}
